\begin_layout Standard
The formalism of Solomonoff Induction measures the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complexity of a description
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by the length of the shortest computer program which produces that description
 as an output.
 To talk about the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shortest computer program
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that does something, you need to specify a space of computer programs,
 which requires a language and interpreter.
 Solomonoff Induction uses Turing machines, or rather, bitstrings that specify
 Turing machines.
 What if you don't like Turing machines? Then there's only a constant complexity
 penalty to design your own Universal Turing Machine that interprets whatever
 code you give it in whatever programming language you like.
 Different inductive formalisms are penalized by a worst-case constant factor
 relative to each other, corresponding to the size of a universal interpreter
 for that formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
